                                Ephesus found Thomas and Zota years later in
                            the desert of Mendis by Mar Menas. Thomas's body was
                            frail and sunburnt. He had dedicated his life to fasting, praying, so
                            that by depriving the body he would purify the soul.  <a href="/805-109" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Susan found
                            the cave in the desert near the village of
                                Mendis and went into it without telling anyone. She went
                            without food and water for several days.  <a href="/819-48" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Mare and his
                            men found an old man who sold utensils for a living in the village of
                                Mendis.
                            He lived in a community of other religious exiles. Stephen and
                                Thomas
                            asked the man to lead them to the exiles.  <a href="/805-53" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Thomas,
                            endeavored to live as an ascetic in the pit near the village of
                                Mendis,
                            but everyone who heard of his plans laughed at him because he had such a
                            privileged upbringing. He was a patrician who had his own estate and
                            slaves and he was the descendent of the great patrician, Ishakuni Bar Brʿy.
                         <a href="/805-60" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/></div><div class="sources"><h4>Personal Names: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-personGrp">
                        <span class="tei-persName"> The blessed Syrians, who
                            fled from those who supported the Council of Chalcedon to the village
                            named <span class="tei-placeName">Mendis</span>
                            at a later time</span>
                    </span>
                </span> <a href="/819-40" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-person">
                        <span class="tei-persName"> A certain blessed man who
                            lived in a cave near <span class="tei-placeName"> the
                                village of Mendis </span></span>
                    </span>
                </span> <a href="/819-44" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-person">
                        <span class="tei-persName">An old man who sold utensils
                            and lived in exile in <span class="tei-placeName">Mendis</span>. </span>
                    </span>
                </span> <a href="/805-54" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-personGrp">
                        <span class="tei-persName">The men and women who lived
